<div className={styles.title}>
# Open Letter to State Legistlature: SPS is Vastly Underfunded By The State
</div>

<div className={styles.card}>
On September 18, 2022, after the teacher strike, an number of parents collaborated on funding analysis resulting in an <a href="https://bit.ly/3E5yRXe">Open Letter showing Washington State is vastfully underfunding all of their schools</a> when compared to other states with
similar cost of living. This letter was <a href="https://www.facebook.com/awongawong/posts/pfbid0EqHMSPktfh8AbHuwLCFz8dJ7UrRw9gFbDipgkSGRr3T6qsg5ECcf8vwqsuXeeVZel">was shared on Facebook</a> and posted on multiple private forums. It made the case that Seattle Public Schools, in particular, is so adversely affected by state legistlation that teacher strikes and service degredation are almost guaranteed.

The letter was emailed on Sept 30th, with a short preamble, to all state senators, representatives, and candidates running for office in districts that intersect Seattle Public Schools.

This post publishes the text of the email sent, and any responses received. Emails have been removed or modified to avoid spam. If you need them, email <a href="mailto:spsbythenumbers@gmail.com">mailto:spsbythenumbers@gmail.com</a>.

<b>Subject:</b> A plan to fund Seattle Public Schools and special education RE: Seattleites demand fixes to state funding laws undermining SPS
</div>

To all parents and educators concerned about, and co-signing, letter on Seattle Public Schools’ budget limitations and inability to fund educators’ compensation, special education, etc. <a href="https://bit.ly/3E5yRXe">https://bit.ly/3E5yRXe</a> (please share):

Washington State – and we as your legislators – have not met our “Paramount Duty” to fully fund ‘basic education.” As the letter to legislators points out, the costs to live in Seattle as an educator far exceed what the State bases its funding formula on – and, “nothing is more basic to education than our educators.”

The biggest hits to Seattle Public Schools’ (SPS’) budget and ability to serve students and pay living wages is the State’s cap on the number of students with disabilities that the State will provide Special Education funding for. This cap is unconscionable, and I believe, unconstitutional. The cap leaves SPS with over $100 million deficit this year!

That means $100 million in levy funds, which would otherwise fund compensation, additional learning services and opportunities must be devoted to providing the services required by federal and state laws to students with disabilities. The lack of funding, as every parent of a child who has had to fight to get a child an IEP knows, leads to a pervasive resistance to providing the services needed for children to be healthy and learn. Parents may spend years trying to have students evaluated for disabilities and having services provided – while their child falls irreversibly farther and farther behind.

I have championed efforts to remove this cap since I became a legislator. We have encountered great resistance – winning only a small increase to serve 13.5% of students.

Closely related is the State’s funding formula providing funds for basically one paraeducator / instructional aide per grade in an elementary school of 450 students, even though students’ learning needs and IEPs may require several IAs per grade. Again, the District’s levy must pay for these staff – whose salaries are truly at an unconscionably low level.

In 2022, we finally passed an 8 fold increase in State funding for school nurses and social workers, which I helped champion, increasing from the State paying for just .07 of a nurse per elementary school to paying for each school to have more than a half time nurse.

In January, I will be offering legislation to remove the unconscionable cap on the number of students for which the State provides special education funds coupled with a major overhaul of evaluations to have meaningful timelines and the State paying for the evaluations.

If successful, Seattle would expect to receive an additional $100 million in funding for the 2023-24 school year and thousands of students would receive the services and supports they need to learn and be healthy.

What will it take to succeed? Please ask to have parent-educator meetings with your legislators (and every candidate) and ask if them to commit to supporting lifting the cap on State funding for students with disabilities. Coordinate with your PTSA, SEA and other organizations and share out the results of those meetings with legislators.

For residents of the 46th, I’m available to meet and to also join you to discuss SPS and education funding and other issues at your PTSA meetings.

Rep. Gerry Pollet,

46th District

<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," />

Gerry.pollet@leg.wa.gov

Dear Representative Pollet,

Thank you for your incredible support and leadership on this issue.  It is hard to imagine a more important issue for Seattle Public Schools right now, and I assure you that Seattle Education Association will be following this issue closely in the upcoming legislative session.

During a recent Seattle School Board work session on the SPS budget (the SPS budget work session agenda is attached), the District shared that the upcoming 2022-23 budget includes approximately $191 million in expenditures for special education, but the State only funds approximately $98.5 million, meaning there is an anticipated shortfall of approximately $92.5 million just related to special education - in just one school year!

<img src="data:image/png;base64," />

While I am sure that there could be some efficiencies in how SPS spends its funds, no amount of efficiencies will ever cover such a large shortfall in special education funding.

As you noted, the 13.5% cap on student apportionment funding (regardless of the actual number of special education students in SPS) is completely arbitrary and unconscionable.  Further, while the impact of the 13.5% cap is perhaps unique to Seattle, school districts across the state are negatively impacted by the State's failure to adequately fund special education.

I would like to note that the State's failure to adequately fund special education does not just hurt our special education students - it hurts all our students and our entire community.

Public schools are the heart of our community.  Public schools are where students from all backgrounds can come together to learn from each other and build a community together.  The promise of public schools is for a more equitable, just and inclusive society.  To fulfill that promise, we need the State to provide the resources and staffing our students and families deserve.

Finally, the Seattle Times recently published an article that our Seattle region has the fourth highest median income in the entire nation.  Adequately funding our schools is not a question of resources, but rather a question of political will -- political will to seek out more progressive revenues and to budget in a manner that truly honors the State's paramount duty of amply funding public schools.

You have demonstrated for many years that you have the political will and courage to stand strong for our public schools. For this we thank you. We, educators, appreciate that you will be working to finally correct the special education funding shortfall, and we will be encouraging your colleagues in the Legislature to stand with you.

Sincerely,

Jennifer Matter (she/her/hers)

President

Seattle Education Association

Thank you to everyone who has joined in this conversation!

I'm glad you included state legislative candidates in your appeal for support.  All of the issues raised are near and dear to me, based on my own lived experience in the SPS system, and the work I have been doing for years to make gains, especially for South End schools.

My vision for public education is that every child is supported in their brilliance in a safe, healthy, and welcoming school environment. My vision is that there are no racial disparities in educational outcomes for our children, that multilingualism is treated as an asset to be supported and that children of every learning style and every ability are provided robust and equitable educational opportunities so they can reach their vast potential. My vision is that there is no use for the phrase “school to prison pipeline” and that schools are a place of safety and care for Black children, Indigenous children and all children of color where diverse cultures are recognized and valued.


We cannot even begin to reach this vision without making good the requests outlined in this letter:



Significantly increase district allocations to adequately fund each district in a way that reflects the district’s economic, geographic, and demographic challenges.
Remove the arbitrary cap on Special Education allocations to fund services for students with disabilities and meet their legal obligations.
Remove the levy cap and other legislation that prevent local governments from solving local problems.


My experience in various advocacy roles in the Seattle Public School system has given me a deep understanding of how the lack of funding impacts all aspects of student, teacher and staff welfare. I’ve been proud to serve as Mercer Middle School PTSA President for several years now, and before that re-establish and lead the PTSA President at Dearborn Park International School.  I have served as vice-president on the Seattle Council of the PTSA, as well as my children’s school Building Leadership and Racial Equity Teams. I am the founding organizer of African American Family gatherings in the Seattle Public Schools and an advisory committee member for the Seattle Public Schools Strategic Plan and member of the SPS Special Education Task Force. I am a resource to many K-12 families, particularly those with an Individual Educational Plan, seeking advocacy support navigating their local schools and districts.



All this to say: I get it, I am with you, and if elected, I will continue this advocacy in the state legislature to achieve these fundamental changes and more.



Emijah Smith,

SPS parent, Mercer Middle School PTSA President, and candidate for 37LD State Rep. Position 2
